            </span>
            <span class="utterance" who="ostlandI" start="551.661" end="x">They left the children but the men were shot near the ditch [common grave]. And one of these people who saved himself from among the men told later how from the ditch where Rabbi Bloch was lying, one heard the cry, "Sma Ysreil" [Hear, O Israel], because it was before daybreak, the time for Krishma [a special prayer for that hour], so he still recited the Krishma and his soul departed on the word Aekhod [the full sentence of the prayer reads: "Hear, O Israel: The Lord our God, the Lord is one"]. The same thing happened the next day, caph aleph [the 21st]. That part of the men whom they had not managed to shoot caph Tammuz [Footnote: The tenth month of the Jewish calendar.] [the 20th of Tammuz] they shot on caph aleph Tammuz [the 21st]. The women who were in the second <a class="term" href="#vothG_lager">lager</a>, that is 16 kilometers from <a class="placename" href="#vothL165">Telsh</a> . . .</span>
