                <span class="">Isaac Ostland</span>:
            </span>
            <span class="utterance" who="ostlandI" start="1301.390" end="x">No, no uniforms, [I went] in civilian clothes. They only gave me the papers and I was granted already all the privileges of a soldier. I was given provisions on the road, a railroad ticket . . . everything. But in <a class="placename" href="#vothL409">Novosibirsk</a>—since that city had no rabbi at the time—I was invited there as rabbi which status I held already from before . . . and thanks to this rabbinical certificates from <a class="placename" href="#vothL409">Novosibirsk</a> where I spent three months time I was subsequently discharged from service by the Lithuanian army in <a class="placename" href="#vothL74">Vilna</a>.</span>
        </li>
                <li>
            <span class="who">
                <span class="">David Boder</span>:
